    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so basically the steel handles the pulling/stretching forces that would otherwise snap the concrete. is there any specific way they actually bond together so the steel doesn't just slip out of the concrete under pressure? like how do the two materials interact once it's all poured and set?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, the steel rebar and concrete do interact after being set. When concrete is mixed and poured, the rebar is typically coated with a laitance (a mixture of cement, water, and sand) that helps it bond to the concrete. As the concrete sets, the hydraulic pressure, heat, and chemical reactions cause the cement paste to penetrate the spaces between the rebar, creating a strong bond between the two. This bond is reinforced by the mechanical connection of the rebar into the concrete and by the chemical reactions between the cement and steel, making the rebar effectively embedded in the concrete.",
      "source": "target",
